description.narrative: (Indonesia): In the last decade, Indonesia has shown significant progress towards a more open and transparent governance practices. However, corruption remains a serious challenge in the country due to ineffective corruption prevention and prosecution efforts. USAID through CEGAH, works to prevent corruption by improving the performance of justice institutions, particularly the Supreme Court and anti-corruption courts; building internal capacity within key government accountability agencies; and strengthening civil society organizations (CSOs) that focus on constructive engagement with the government to enhance public service delivery. In 2018, the contract was amended to address the nexus between corruption and violent extremism; thus each component has been expanded to include accountability activities that also reduce Indonesia's susceptibility to violent extremism. The CEGAH's program highest level result is "Community of Accountability Improved," and focuses much of its efforts at the national level. . With FY 2019 funds, USAID through CEGAH will continue its on-going activities on several prevention strengthening systems within the justice sector and key accountability agencies. USAID will also support the anti-corruption agency's transformation as mandated by the new law through civil society input. USAID contributes to the Indo-Pacific Strategy and the U.S. Mission objective of helping Indonesia take meaningful steps to promote sustained justice-sector reform and respect for the rule of law, and to enhance law enforcement and military professionalism and accountability, in order to improve access to justice, and increase citizen confidence.....
